{"source_key":"sha256-a93d5e12b74542ffeb860fd5a6e2a70f","record_index":109,"record_hash":"sha256:db486f89efd2b07a61f42b28f9afcca3f34edc872d614942556e2292692fdae3","timestamp":"2026-06-03T08:51:01.293Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Short answer: **no, not directly**.\n\nPR #13854 does **not** let arbitrary user input become a command. The new backend terminal detection uses a fixed allowlist in [terminal.rs]([REDACTED:path]), filters by platform, then probes with `which`; `open_in_terminal` still matches `terminal_id` against known terminal names before spawning in [open/mod.rs]([REDACTED:path]). Args are passed with `Command::arg`, not shell interpolation.\n\nThe real caveat: it does lean harder on `PATH`. If an attacker can poison GitButler’s process `PATH` with a fake allowlisted binary like `gnome-terminal`, `wezterm`, `wt`, etc., GitButler may auto-select it and later launch it by bare name in [open/mod.rs]([REDACTED:path]). That’s a **PATH-hijack hardening issue**, not a new arbitrary command execution primitive from the PR alone.\n\nMy fix: resolve the executable with `which`, then spawn the resolved absolute path, and reject unknown `terminal_id` before doing any lookup. That closes the annoying “checked one thing, launched another thing” gap.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-06-03T08:51:01.293Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}